Did this happen in your host or runtime workbench?

The reason why you got the NPE is becuase pde.core was disabled.

Rafael, when a bundle is unresolved and has 0 unresolved constraints, we 
assume it was not picked because a better one was picked, which is not the 
case here.  Is there another reason that could result in an empty array of 
unresolved constraints?

In normal cases, that is the reason. Also, if someone calls State.resolve
passing a subset of bundles to be resolved, a resolvable bundle that is not in
the given subset will remain unresolved, but I don't think you are doing that.

What is curious in this case is that only bundles that had hand-crafted bundle
manifests were not resolved. 

Just to get things straight: the NPE is an error during runtime, while the log
entries under:

!ENTRY org.eclipse.pde.core 2 1 Apr 02, 2004 10:18:52.856
!MESSAGE Problems while scanning external plug-ins

were created by PDE while resolving its own private State, not by the OSGi layer
during bundle resolution. Right?

Nick, please confirm where the log was collected from (host/runtime) and where 
the dynamic classpath was not resolved (host/runtime), so we could make sense 
out of the unresolved entries.

The problem was with my host, not my runtime workbench.  The log entries are
from the host as well.

There is more than one minute between the NPEs and the warning entries, and I
believe they are not related. And also seems that that warning message
("Problems while scanning external plug-ins") used to be generated by PDE while
scanning plugins for the target platform, but not anymore since M8, what really
puzzles me.

Rafael, as per your request, since the 0330 we put back the "problems while 
scanning external plug-ins" warnings.

Although I was unable to reproduce this specific one, recent work in the last 
couple of days on making the initializer resilient in the face of operation 
canceling by Platform/Core ought to take care of this one.
